–Overleden","1265–Female":"1265–Overleden","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1299–Male":"1299–Overleden","1285–Male":"1285–Overleden","1243–Male":"1243–Overleden","1249–Female":"1249–Overleden","about 1260":"circa 1260","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1299":"1299","1453":"1453","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","about 1285":"circa 1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hele Estate, Cornwood, Devonshire, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1260–":"about 1260–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1292–Female":"1292–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1299–Male":"1299–Deceased","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1243–Male":"1243–Deceased","1249–Female":"1249–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1299":"1299","1453":"1453","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","about 1285":"about 1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hele Estate, Cornwood, Devonshire, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hele","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Heal  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heal","meanings":["English:","topographic or habitational name for someone who lived in or by a nook or hollow, or at a place called with this word (from Middle English <i>hele</i>, Old English <i>heale</i>, dative singular of <i>healh</i> ‘nook or hollow’). Hele in Somerset derives from this word, but the surname arises chiefly from one or more of the many minor localities named Heal(e) or Hele in Devon. In southwestern England and Kent this is an equivalent of   Hale  .","in the southeast Midlands of England, perhaps a variant of   Hell   1."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":55,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":68,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":77,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Hele III Lord of Hele was born about 1260, in Cornwood, Devon, England, his father, Sir Roger Hele II Knight of Hele, was 18 and his mother, Lady Roger Hele, was 12. He had at least 1 son with Lady Roger Hele."},"et":{"about 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1299–Male":"1299–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1243–Male":"1243–Surnud","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1299":"1299","1453":"1453","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","about 1285":"umbes 1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hele Estate, Cornwood, Devonshire, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1292–Female":"1292–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1299–Male":"1299–Kuollut","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1243–Male":"1243–Kuollut","1249–Female":"1249–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1299":"1299","1453":"1453","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","about 1285":"noin 1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hele Estate, Cornwood, Devonshire, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1260–":"environ 1260–Décédé","1260–Male":"1260–Décé